postcontent:
Up for sale is a 1901 M91 mosin nagant rifle made at the sestoryetsk arsenal. These are pretty uncommon as sestoryetsk stopped making rifles after WWI during the Russian revolution. This one has a pretty interesting history. At some point it was captured during WWI by the Austrians and they added sling hangers behind the front and rear sling slots, some time after that was done it went to the balkans,it has a bulgarian pinecone cartouche on the stock and a Romanian CAR cartouche. The bolt doesnt, match and the floorplate is one number off, has the "balkan wedge" underneath the rear sight. The bore is dark but has strong rifling and isint pitted at all. In pretty good shape for a 113 year old rifle. $325

title: For Sale:  Benjamin Genesis .22 cal Air Rifle w/ Nitro Piston and Silencer
postcontent:
2 month old Benjamin Genesis .22 caliber air rifle in immaculate condition with an absolutely top notch Hawke Sport Optics scope. If you have never heard of or never shot/used a Nitro Piston springer, you will be pleasantly surprised. Smoother cocking effort, much more consistent velocity from shot to shot and has much less recoil than a standard springer. I bought this gun 2 months ago from Big 5and then after doing a little research on what scopes work best on springers, I went to AOA and purchased a Hawke Sport Optics 4-16x50mm scope with illuminated mildot reticle. If you ask anybody who knows anything about air rifle optics and their longevity - you will get the same answer every time: and that is if you have an air rifle and want a scope that will stand up to the intense recoil of spring piston rifles, you buy a Hawke Sport scope - period. One really nice advantage of this particular rifle is that instead of an 11mm dovetailed receiver, you have an integrated picatinny rail that accepts any weaver style rings/bases making choices for rings and their availabilty quite a bit easier. 

This rifle is advertised to shoot at 950fps with alloy pellets and 800 fps using a standard lead (14.7 gr). As I have a chrony I set it up and tested the velocity of this bad boy and was surprised yet again at this rifle. With Gamo PBA ammo, I had an average velocity of 970-990 fps and with the Crosman Premiers I was getting between 810-825 fps - so having an air rifle that actually shoots the velocities that it advertises was refreshing to say the least. What was really nice was that the standard deviation being a scant 9 fps! 

In all honesty, I would rather like to keep this rifle but now that I have a Benjamin Discovery (my first PCP) thanks to my fabulous wifes Fathers Day present, I really can't keep them both. First of all, I don't want my wife thinking that I I like the Genesis better than her present; secondly if I sell my Genesis then I can buy a nicer Hawke Sport scope that has a higher power range and side wheel for field target - thirdly as the Disco's report hovers around 110 dB out of the box I can buy a TK suppressor/muzzle break - then order a good amount of pelllets so that I have a wider variety of ammo for breaking in and testing the Discovery. The Genesis is super quiet and absolutely super accurate with a wide variety of pellet types - (though it favors Crosman Premier 14.3 gr bulk pellets) and I shoot those most often. In addition to the Premiers, I have also had very good accuracy results with most all of the Benjamin Discovery pellets especially the pointed hunting version. In addition to the Benjamins, the best hunting pellet that I have tried are the Predator Polymags in the 16 grain version. What really surprised me was that those Polymags were the 2nd most accurate pellets overall - putting 7 rounds in just under 5/8" at 33 yards (Yes I konw that everybody and their brother shoots either 5 or 10 shot groups and Im sure that I am breaking the unwritten code of target shooting but 7 round groups are the best of both worlds. I primarily use my air rifles for pigeon control but I do shoot the occasional silhouette match or a field target match when its not 145 degrees outside in the valley - for all of the competition shooting that I have done with the Genesis I use the Crosmans but all of my pest control/general small game hunting is done using the Polymags. At my friends dairy where pigeons fly in and out by the thousands I rarely get a pigeon that has a direct hit in the breast area that flys away. I try to keep most of my shots under 50 yards so that I have a much higher chance of making humane kills and all of my shots that are under 30 yards using Polymags go all the way through both Eurasion doves and pigeons too!

If you are interested in an absolutey first rate spring gun package that will wallop pigeons, crows, eurasion doves, squirrels, rats, raccoons or anything of the like - this is the set up for you! The way that this rifle/scope is configured and being a spring rifle, it isnt a walk in the park to shoot accurately but its not rocket science either. I use the artillery hold with all of the springers that I have ever owned/used and the Genesis is no different in that regard, even with the Nitro Piston cylinder. If you have never heard of an artillery hold in reference to air rifles I'll explain it in the easiest way possible; essentially when you are shooting whether from a bench or offhand, keep a loose hold on the rifle with your bridge hand and keep it loose in your shoulder. The only pressure you really want to have on the gun is on the pistol grip. By doing so you really wring out the accuracy of this one. Once you master the artillery hold - man oh man will your hit/kill/X's increase! Anyway - I am in Gilbert AZ so if anyone is local and would like to pickup locally instead of shipping - just text me @ REDACTED. Text is preferred for the first point of contact becasue I will not answer a phone call from anyone that is not in my phone book already. If you don't text and have to call instead, just leave me a voicemail and I will return your call promptly. Pics are available via text/email if requested so just let me know and I will send out right away! 

I will also include a full box of the Crosman Premiers 625ct. and a partial tin of the Discovery pointed hunting pellets of which there is about 60ct left. If there is anytihng that I am missing or if there is something else that you need to know, my number is above.

For sale from NC23 GUNS:
 3 Yugo MAUSERS for sale all great used surplus condition.

M48
M48 BO
M 24/27

Non are matching numbers which is very typical.
The Zastava M48 is a post World War II Yugoslavian version of the German Karabiner 98k designed Mauser and the Belgian/Czech designed m24 series. After World War II, the Yugoslavs took this design and incorporated minor modifications. Although very similar in general appearance to that of the German rifle, many of the parts of these two rifles are not interchangeable, especially the bolt and related action parts. The main difference between the M48 and the K98k is that the M48 uses an intermediate-length receiver. They are usually easily identified by the top handguard, which extends behind the rear sight and ends just in front of the receiver ring, although this feature exists on other models as well. M48's are regarded as a military surplus firearm and can be collected.

title: For Sale:   HIGH PRICED AMMO OR NO AMMO AT ALL
postcontent:
WILL LEAD PLANT CLOSURE CAUSE HIGH PRICED AMMO OR NO AMMO AT ALL?
The effect on the right to keep and bear arms is obvious. 
The Herculaneum smelter was the only smelter in the United States which produced lead bullion from raw lead ore that was mined nearby in Missouri’s extensive lead deposits, giving the smelter its “primary” designation. The lead bullion produced was then sold to lead product producers, including ammunition manufacturers for use in conventional ammunition components such as projectiles, projectile cores, and primers. 
Without ammunition, a gun is just a club. The government knows this, and in light of the ongoing project of arming federal agencies to the teeth with millions of rounds of ammunition and military-grade weapons and vehicles, the EPA’s closing of the Doe Run plant, although not a direct assault on the right to keep and bear arms, can be seen as another step toward civilian disarmament. 
While a few other media outlets have reported on the closure, none has connected this dot to a couple of others in the overall plan to leave Americans without weapons and ammunition.
First, the EPA’s closing of the country’s last lead smelting facility follows close on the heels (within a little over a month) of Secretary of State John Kerry’s signing of the United Nations’ Arms Trade Treaty (ATT) “on behalf of President Barack Obama and the people of the United States.”
Article 3 of that agreement outlaws the buying, selling, trading, or transferring by civilians of all “ammunition/munitions fired, launched or delivered by the conventional arms.”
By making it impossible to manufacture ammunition, it becomes impossible for civilians to own it. Mind you, such prohibitions do not apply to government. In fact, under the Arms Trade Treaty, the national governments of member countries are given monopoly control of the entire ammunition stockpile of that country.
Hope you are stocking up on ammo.

Item 4A (305gr. Hard Cast gas Checked LFN) is designed for super deep penetration on large game. The big flat nose keeps the bullet penetrating straight and thus deep. You can expect a good three + feet of penetration in normal flesh and bone. The flat nose also does considerably more damage than a round nosed type of bullet as the flat nose cuts and smashes it way through living matter, while round nosed bullets tend to slip and slide through matter, doing much less damage along the bullet’s path and achieving more shallow penetration due to getting sideways while “slipping and sliding” through matter.
